{{for|the optical lens design figure|Charles Gorrie Wynne}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}} {{Use British English|date=March 2016}} '''Charles Griffith Wynne''' (14 August 1815 – 3 March 1874), later known as '''Charles Wynne-Finch''', was a Liberal Tory politician and a Member of Parliament for [[Caernarfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Caernarfon]].
==Early life== Wynne was born in London in 1815. He was the oldest son of [[Charles Griffith-Wynne]], MP for [[Caernarvonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Caernarvonshire]] (1830–1832) and his wife, Sarah Hildyard, the daughter of Rev. Henry Hildyard.<ref name=Blain>{{cite book | pages = 93–94 | last = Blain | first = Rev. Michael | title = The Canterbury Association (1848-1852): A Study of Its Members’ Connections | year = 2007 | publisher = Project Canterbury | location = Christchurch | url = http://anglicanhistory.org/nz/blain_canterbury2007.pdf | accessdate = 3 April 2013 }}</ref> His paternal grandfather was the MP [[Charles Finch (MP)|Charles Finch]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hon. Charles Finch |url= http://thepeerage.com/p5716.htm#i57157 |publisher=The Peerage |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> He received his education at [[Eton College|Eton]] and at [[Christ Church, Oxford]], from where he graduated with a BA in 1837.<ref name=Blain /> He also represented the university at [[cricket]], playing two matches for the [[Oxford University cricket team]].<ref name="cricpro">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/23454.html | title=Player Profile: Charles Wynne-Finch | publisher=ESPN CricInfo | accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>
==Career== Wynne joined the [[Canterbury Association]] on 25 October 1849, and on 8 November of that year joined the management committee. Together with [[James FitzGerald (New Zealand politician)|James FitzGerald]], he applied pressure on [[John Hutt]] on 26 March 1850 to straighten out the affairs of the association, which caused Hutt to resign three days later.<ref name=Blain /> Wynne was member of the Caernarfon constituency from the [[United Kingdom general election, 1859|1859 general election]] to the [[United Kingdom general election, 1865|1865 general election]]. He was [[High Sheriff of Denbighshire]] in 1869.<ref name=Blain />
==Family and death== Wynne's sister, [[Charlotte Godley|Charlotte Griffith-Wynne]], married [[John Robert Godley]] in September 1846, who later became to be regarded as the founder of [[Canterbury Region|Canterbury]] in New Zealand.<ref name=Blain /> On 15 June 1840, Wynne had married Laura Susan Pollen, the daughter of Richard Pollen (1786–1838) and Anne Cockerell. His wife died on 7 March 1851.<ref name=Blain /> He remarried in 1863 to Jamesina Joyce Ellen Styleman Le Strang, the widow of [[Henry L'Estrange Styleman Le Strange]] (d. 1862). She was the daughter of John Stewart (MP).<ref name=Blain />
He died on 3 March 1874 at 4 Rue Solferino, Paris, France. His estate was probated at £35,000.<ref name=Blain />
