[[File:US Grant in 1885.jpg|thumb|[[Ulysses S. Grant]], working on his memoirs in 1885. His ''[[Personal Memoirs of Ulysses S. Grant|Personal Memoirs]]'' is considered by historians to be among the best by a U.S. President.]]
Many [[President of the United States|presidents of the United States]] have written [[autobiographies]] about their presidencies and/or (some periods of) their life before their time in office. Some 19th-century U.S. presidents who wrote autobiographies are James Buchanan and Ulysses S. Grant, though Grant's autobiography is about his time as General during the U.S. Civil War and not about his presidency. Some of the more recent U.S. presidential autobiographies, such as Bill Clinton's, George W. Bush's, and Barack Obama's (written and published before he was elected president) sold well enough to earn them millions of dollars.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7331834.stm |title=Americas &#124; Clintons' earnings exceed $100m |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-04-05 |accessdate=2013-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Simon Mann, Washington |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/man-of-steel-barely-rates-a-mention-in-bush-memoirs-20101110-17nrf.html |title='Man of Steel' barely rates a mention in Bush memoirs |publisher=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date= |accessdate=2013-04-08}}</ref>

